				<li class="wordpress even thread-even depth-1 social-comment social-clearfix social-wordpress" id="li-comment-376">
<div class="social-comment-inner social-clearfix" id="comment-376">
	<div class="social-comment-header">
		<div class="social-comment-author ">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/f62378cb323e102472c606e8083fd9ce?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/f62378cb323e102472c606e8083fd9ce?s=80&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /><cite class="social-fn fn"><a href='http://joemillerjd.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Joseph Miller</a></cite>		</div>
		<!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		<div class="social-comment-meta social-comment-meta-wordpress">
			<span class="social-posted-from">
								<span>View</span>
							</span>
			<a href="http://werblog.com/2011/07/the-next-network-policy-battle/#comment-376" class="social-posted-when" target="_blank">July 18, 2011</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="social-comment-body">
				<p>I&#8217;m always left puzzled by the fact that network policy and social policy are still very much addressed in silos, even though on the surface everyone argues that progressive network policies are designed to promote those ends.  If network policy is genuinely going to pursue societal ends, an ability to empathize with the poverty mindset seems to be at least as important as the technical issues.  </p>
<p>The pursuit of happiness is at the core of American notions of independence.  But happiness itself can seem unattainable if we perpetuate objective prerequisites.  This causes people in the most dire conditions to stop striving, when the likelihood of achieving those prerequisites is statistically impossible.</p>
	</div>
